Perfect â€” youâ€™ve got a **very strong frontend setup** already.
Letâ€™s now add a **visualization block** that shows the **insertion dates of MongoDB items** (or basically a chart of when news was added to your cluster).

We can easily do this with a **chart component** using `recharts`, which integrates beautifully into your `Posts` page.

---

## ğŸ§± Goal

Weâ€™ll display a **small visualization block** (like a bar or line chart) showing **how many MongoDB â€œnewsâ€ items were inserted per day**.

It will:

* Fetch the same data you already load from `/api/content`
* Filter only `type: "news"`
* Count how many per date
* Display that as a chart (using `recharts`)

---

## ğŸ§© Step 1: Install the library

In your project root, run:

```bash
npm install recharts
```

---

## ğŸ§  Step 2: Create a new file

Create a new component file:

```
frontend/src/components/NewsInsertChart.tsx
```

Paste this code inside:

```tsx
import { useMemo } from "react";
import {
  LineChart,
  Line,
  XAxis,
  YAxis,
  CartesianGrid,
  Tooltip,
  ResponsiveContainer,
} from "recharts";

interface NewsItem {
  date: string;
  type: string;
}

interface Props {
  newsItems: NewsItem[];
}

export default function NewsInsertChart({ newsItems }: Props) {
  // Count items by day
  const data = useMemo(() => {
    const counts: Record<string, number> = {};

    newsItems.forEach(item => {
      const day = new Date(item.date).toISOString().split("T")[0];
      counts[day] = (counts[day] || 0) + 1;
    });

    return Object.entries(counts)
      .sort(([a], [b]) => (a < b ? -1 : 1))
      .map(([date, count]) => ({ date, count }));
  }, [newsItems]);

  if (data.length === 0) {
    return (
      <div className="text-center text-gray-500 text-sm p-4">
        No MongoDB news available for visualization.
      </div>
    );
  }

  return (
    <div className="bg-white rounded-2xl p-6 shadow-md mt-8">
      <h3 className="text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-gray-800">
        ğŸ—“ï¸ MongoDB Insert Activity (by Date)
      </h3>
      <ResponsiveContainer width="100%" height={250}>
        <LineChart data={data}>
          <CartesianGrid strokeDasharray="3 3" stroke="#e2e8f0" />
          <XAxis dataKey="date" tick={{ fontSize: 12 }} />
          <YAxis allowDecimals={false} tick={{ fontSize: 12 }} />
          <Tooltip />
          <Line
            type="monotone"
            dataKey="count"
            stroke="#16a34a"
            strokeWidth={2}
            dot={{ r: 4 }}
            activeDot={{ r: 6 }}
          />
        </LineChart>
      </ResponsiveContainer>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

## ğŸ§© Step 3: Integrate into your `Posts.tsx`

1ï¸âƒ£ At the top of `Posts.tsx`, import the chart:

```tsx
import NewsInsertChart from "../components/NewsInsertChart";
```

2ï¸âƒ£ Inside your main JSX return â€” ideally **below the MongoDB News Section**, add:

```tsx
{/* Visualization block for MongoDB insert dates */}
{newsContent.length > 0 && (
  <NewsInsertChart newsItems={newsContent} />
)}
```

So, itâ€™ll appear after your line:

```tsx
</section>
```

for the newsContent section.

---

## ğŸ¨ Result

Youâ€™ll now see a nice **chart with green lines** showing how many MongoDB â€œnewsâ€ documents were inserted each day.
If your scraper adds new ones daily, youâ€™ll see the line grow automatically.

---

## âš¡ Optional Improvements

* Replace `<LineChart>` with `<BarChart>` for bars:

  ```tsx
  import { BarChart, Bar, XAxis, YAxis, CartesianGrid, Tooltip, ResponsiveContainer } from "recharts";
  ...
  <BarChart data={data}>
    <CartesianGrid strokeDasharray="3 3" />
    <XAxis dataKey="date" />
    <YAxis />
    <Tooltip />
    <Bar dataKey="count" fill="#10b981" />
  </BarChart>
  ```
* Combine both for dual view (bar + line)
* Add live updates using `setInterval(fetchContent, 60000)` to refresh every minute

